commit.message:
Install import hook earlier during pytest initialization (#143)

The pytest plugin does not work at all in this very common scenario:

- Application/library uses a conftest.py file with pytest configuration
- This conftest.py imports application/library modules.

Even worse, no matter what is passed as the ‘--typeguard-packages=’
command line argument, no warnings or errors will be reported at all.
Typeguard will be fully silent. this this makes it seem the code is
fully correct, while in reality the code is not checked by typeguard
*at all*. Oops. 💥 🙈 😱

The problem is that the pytest plugin used the ‘pytest_sessionstart()’
hook, which triggers only after conftest.py files (or other pytest
configuration files) have been loaded already. This is too late to
install the import hook: the targeted modules may have been imported
already at this point!

This pull request fixes this problem in the following way:

- Use ‘pytest_configure()’ instead of ‘pytest_sessionstart()’, since
  the former triggers before any conftest files are loaded.

- Make it impossible to silently skip checks for packages specified on
  the command line that cannot actually be checked. In those situations,
  raise an error with all the details. Example for
  ‘--typeguard-packages=sys’:

  INTERNALERROR> RuntimeError: typeguard cannot check these packages that are already imported: sys

See also:

- https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable/reference.html#pytest.hookspec.pytest_configure
- https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable/reference.html#pytest.hookspec.pytest_sessionstart

commit.message: Fixed missing bytes support for Literal
Check for nested literals and illegal literal values
Updated the changelog

Fixed NoReturn being None on Python 3.7 and lower

It was introduced a lot earlier than Literal so they should not be imported in the same conditional block.
Fixed ImportError on py3.7 and lower
Added release date

Fixed coverage calculation

Doing this with the pytest plugin causes a lot of lines to be missed.
Enabled coveralls parallel build reporting

Don't test against PyPy3 on Travis

Travis only has a very old release of PyPy which fails tests due to interpreter bugs.

Bumped the minimum Python version to 3.5.3

Python 3.5.2 is just too buggy to properly work with typing_extensions.

Added the globals and locals arguments to check_type()

Fixes #62. Fixes #129.
Added function annotation for isinstance() in the user guide
Improved support for typing_extensions

Removed conditional import of typing.Type

Now that we only support Python 3.5.2+, this is no longer needed.

Ensured that recursive types work properly

This excludes check_type() since this requires a call memo.
Pass memo to check_type() from check_typed_dict()

Fixed erroneous TypeErrors with Protocols

Fixes #99.
Use Python 3.8 for flake8

Fixed forward references in TypedDict not being resolved

Fixes #123.

Added support for typing.NoReturn

Fixes #131.
Added release date
Added paragraph about mock support

Added note about totality in TypedDict

Closes #101.

Rearranged the documentation

Fixes #116.

Fixed error message when checking against a Union[..., Literal[...]]

Fixes #113.

Fixed checking against bound type variables with check_type() without a call memo

Fixes #122.
Updated the version history
